        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 4 ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-4">
          <h2 class="exp-head">4 &middot; Convolution &mdash; flip and slide</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">y(&tau;) = &int; x(s) h(&tau; - s) ds, animated as overlap area at each shift</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To evaluate the convolution of two signals by the flip-and-slide method, watching one signal reflected and dragged across the other while the shaded overlap area at each shift is accumulated point-by-point into the output y(&tau;).</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>Convolution combines two signals into a third that measures how much they overlap as one slides past the other. For continuous time:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">y(&tau;) = (x * h)(&tau;) = &int; x(s) &middot; h(&tau; - s) ds<br>steps: flip h to h(-s), shift to h(&tau;-s), multiply, integrate<br>output length spans the sum of the two supports</div>
            <p>The recipe is fixed: take the second signal, <b>flip</b> it left-to-right, <b>shift</b> it to position &tau;, <b>multiply</b> it sample-by-sample against the first, and <b>integrate</b> (sum the overlap area). That single number is y at shift &tau;. Sliding &tau; from far left to far right traces the whole output. Here the integral is approximated by a Riemann sum over a fine grid, which is exactly the discrete convolution sum y[n] = &Sigma; x[k] h[n - k]. Convolution is commutative, associative and distributive, and convolving any signal with an impulse returns the signal unchanged.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open the <b>Simulation</b> and pick shapes for x(s) (cyan) and h(s) (purple).</li>
            <li>Press <b>Play</b>. The flipped-and-shifted copy of h slides across x; the green shaded region is their instantaneous product overlap.</li>
            <li>The bottom plot grows: each shift contributes one output sample equal to the shaded area, so the curve y(&tau;) is drawn as the slide proceeds.</li>
            <li>Drag the <b>shift &tau;</b> slider by hand to freeze any position and read the overlap area.</li>
            <li>Convolve a pulse with itself to get a triangle; convolve anything with the impulse to recover it unchanged.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3>Flip-and-slide</h3>
                <canvas id="cvCv" width="660" height="300"></canvas>
                <h3 style="margin-top:14px;">Output y(&tau;) accumulated</h3>
                <canvas id="cvOut" width="660" height="200"></canvas>
                <div class="legend">
                  <span><i style="background:#67e8f9"></i> x(s)</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#a78bfa"></i> h(&tau;-s)</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#86efac"></i> overlap area</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#fbbf24"></i> y(&tau;)</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Signals</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>x(s)</label>
                    <select id="cvX"><option value="rect">Rectangle</option><option value="tri">Triangle</option><option value="exp">Decaying exp</option><option value="impulse">Impulse</option></select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>h(s)</label>
                    <select id="cvH"><option value="rect">Rectangle</option><option value="tri">Triangle</option><option value="exp">Decaying exp</option><option value="impulse">Impulse</option></select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Shift &tau;</label><input type="range" id="cvTau" min="-5" max="5" step="0.05" value="-5"><span class="val" id="cvTauv">-5.0</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Speed</label><input type="range" id="cvSp" min="0.2" max="4" step="0.2" value="1.4"><span class="val" id="cvSpv">1.4x</span></div>
                  <div class="btns"><button class="btn cyan" id="cvPlay">Play</button><button class="btn ghost" id="cvReset">Reset</button></div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Shift &tau;</div><div class="v sm" id="cvShown">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Overlap area</div><div class="v sm" id="cvArea">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">y(&tau;) now</div><div class="v sm" id="cvY">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Peak y</div><div class="v sm" id="cvPk">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help">The green area equals one output sample. Sum over all shifts and you have the full convolution.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="4"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Oppenheim, Willsky &amp; Nawab</b> &mdash; Signals and Systems, 2nd ed., Ch. 2. Prentice Hall.</li>
            <li><b>Lathi</b> &mdash; Linear Systems and Signals, 2nd ed., Sec. 2.4. Oxford.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Signals and Systems: Convolution, vlab.co.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
