        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 5 ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-5">
          <h2 class="exp-head">5 &middot; Fourier series &amp; Gibbs</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Partial sum of N harmonics approaching square / sawtooth / triangle</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To reconstruct a periodic waveform as a finite sum of harmonically related sinusoids, to watch the partial sum approach the target as the number of harmonics N grows, and to observe the Gibbs overshoot that persists near discontinuities however large N becomes.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>A periodic signal of fundamental &omega;0 is an infinite weighted sum of sinusoids at integer multiples of &omega;0. For the odd waveforms here only sine terms appear:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">x(t) = &Sigma; b_n sin(n &omega;0 t)<br>Square: b_n = 4/(n&pi;) for odd n, else 0<br>Sawtooth: b_n = 2(-1)^(n+1)/(n&pi;)<br>Triangle: b_n = 8/(n&pi;)^2 with alternating sign, odd n</div>
            <p>The N-term partial sum is the best least-squares fit of N harmonics to the target. As N grows the sum converges to the waveform everywhere it is continuous. At a jump it converges to the midpoint, but the overshoot just before the jump does not shrink &mdash; it settles at about 9 percent of the jump height no matter how many terms you add. This is the <b>Gibbs phenomenon</b>; the ringing simply narrows toward the discontinuity. The amplitude spectrum b_n falls off as 1/n for the square and sawtooth (slow, because of the jump) but as 1/n&sup2; for the continuous triangle (fast).</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open the <b>Simulation</b> and choose a target waveform.</li>
            <li>Drag <b>harmonics N</b> from 1 upward. The orange partial sum sharpens toward the grey target.</li>
            <li>For the square and sawtooth, watch the ears near the jumps &mdash; the <b>overshoot</b> stat stays near 9 percent however large N is.</li>
            <li>Switch to the triangle: convergence is far faster and the overshoot vanishes, because there is no discontinuity.</li>
            <li>Read the spectrum bars; lit bars are included in the sum, dim bars are the harmonics still left out.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3>Partial sum vs target</h3>
                <canvas id="fsCv" width="660" height="300"></canvas>
                <h3 style="margin-top:14px;">Harmonic amplitude spectrum</h3>
                <canvas id="fsSp" width="660" height="170"></canvas>
                <div class="legend">
                  <span><i style="background:#9aa0aa"></i> target</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#fbbf24"></i> partial sum</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#67e8f9"></i> included harmonic</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>Waveform</label>
                    <select id="fsWave"><option value="square">Square</option><option value="saw">Sawtooth</option><option value="triangle">Triangle</option></select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Harmonics N</label><input type="range" id="fsN" min="1" max="60" step="1" value="5"><span class="val" id="fsNv">5</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Show terms</label>
                    <select id="fsShow"><option value="0">Sum only</option><option value="1">Sum + sinusoids</option></select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="btns"><button class="btn cyan" id="fsAnim">Sweep N</button><button class="btn ghost" id="fsReset">Reset</button></div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Terms used</div><div class="v" id="fsTerms">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Overshoot</div><div class="v sm" id="fsOver">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">RMS error</div><div class="v sm" id="fsErr">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Roll-off</div><div class="v sm" id="fsRoll">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="help">Gibbs overshoot near a jump converges to roughly 8.95 percent of the jump &mdash; it never disappears.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="5"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Oppenheim, Willsky &amp; Nawab</b> &mdash; Signals and Systems, 2nd ed., Ch. 3. Prentice Hall.</li>
            <li><b>Stein &amp; Shakarchi</b> &mdash; Fourier Analysis, Ch. 2 (Gibbs phenomenon). Princeton.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Signals and Systems: Fourier Series, vlab.co.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
        </section>

        <!-- ============ EXPERIMENT 6 ============ -->
        <section class="exp" id="exp-6">
          <h2 class="exp-head">6 &middot; Sampling &amp; aliasing</h2>
          <div class="exp-sub">Sample x(t) at fs and watch the reconstruction alias when fs &lt; 2 f</div>
          <div class="secbar">
            <button class="stab on" data-sec="aim">Aim</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="theory">Theory</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="proc">Procedure</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="sim">Simulation</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="quiz">Self-assessment</button>
            <button class="stab" data-sec="ref">References</button>
          </div>

          <div class="sec aim on"><div class="prose">To sample a sinusoid at a chosen rate fs, to reconstruct a band-limited signal from those samples, and to observe how a too-low rate folds the true frequency down to a lower alias frequency that the samples cannot distinguish from the original.</div></div>

          <div class="sec theory"><div class="prose">
            <p>Sampling reads a continuous signal at evenly spaced instants spaced T = 1/fs apart. The Nyquist-Shannon theorem fixes when the samples keep all the information:</p>
            <div class="eqblock">fs &gt;= 2 f_max (Nyquist criterion)<br>Nyquist frequency = fs / 2<br>alias: f_alias = | f - fs &middot; round(f / fs) |</div>
            <p>If the signal frequency f exceeds the Nyquist frequency fs/2, the samples are identical to those of a lower-frequency sinusoid: the high frequency is <b>aliased</b> down by folding around multiples of fs. A reconstructor that assumes the lowest possible frequency consistent with the samples then draws the wrong, lower-frequency wave &mdash; the apparent frequency is f_alias above. Here the reconstruction is the ideal band-limited sinc interpolation of the samples, so when fs is high enough it overlays the original exactly, and when fs is too low it collapses onto the alias. The familiar wagon-wheel effect on film is exactly this.</p>
          </div></div>

          <div class="sec proc"><ol class="steps">
            <li>Open the <b>Simulation</b>. The grey curve is the true continuous sinusoid; the cyan dots are the samples.</li>
            <li>Set the <b>signal frequency f</b> and the <b>sampling rate fs</b>.</li>
            <li>Lower fs below 2f and watch the orange sinc reconstruction peel away from the grey original and lock onto a slower alias.</li>
            <li>Read the <b>alias frequency</b> stat and the <b>Nyquist</b> verdict (OK or aliasing) updating live.</li>
            <li>Set fs to exactly 2f to sit on the Nyquist edge, then nudge it either way to cross the boundary.</li>
          </ol></div>

          <div class="sec sim">
            <div class="layout">
              <div class="panel">
                <h3>Original, samples &amp; reconstruction</h3>
                <canvas id="saCv" width="660" height="320"></canvas>
                <div class="legend">
                  <span><i style="background:#9aa0aa"></i> true x(t)</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#67e8f9"></i> samples</span>
                  <span><i style="background:#fbbf24"></i> sinc reconstruction</span>
                </div>
                <div class="help"><b>Verdict:</b> <span id="saVerdict" style="color:#86efac">--</span></div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <div class="panel">
                  <h3>Controls</h3>
                  <div class="row"><label>Signal f</label><input type="range" id="saF" min="0.5" max="8" step="0.1" value="2"><span class="val" id="saFv">2.0 Hz</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Sample fs</label><input type="range" id="saFs" min="1" max="20" step="0.25" value="10"><span class="val" id="saFsv">10.0 Hz</span></div>
                  <div class="row"><label>Reconstruct</label>
                    <select id="saRec"><option value="1">Sinc interpolation</option><option value="0">Hide reconstruction</option></select>
                  </div>
                  <div class="btns"><button class="btn ghost" id="saReset">Reset</button></div>
                  <div class="stats">
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Nyquist fs/2</div><div class="v sm" id="saNyq">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Samples / s</div><div class="v sm" id="saSpr">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Alias freq</div><div class="v sm" id="saAlias">--</div></div>
                    <div class="stat"><div class="k">Ratio fs/2f</div><div class="v sm" id="saRatio">--</div></div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="sec quiz"><div class="quiz" data-quiz="6"></div></div>

          <div class="sec ref"><ul class="refs">
            <li><b>Oppenheim, Willsky &amp; Nawab</b> &mdash; Signals and Systems, 2nd ed., Ch. 7. Prentice Hall.</li>
            <li><b>Proakis &amp; Manolakis</b> &mdash; Digital Signal Processing, 4th ed., Sec. 1.4. Pearson.</li>
            <li><b>Virtual Labs (IIT)</b> &mdash; Signals and Systems: Sampling and Aliasing, vlab.co.in.</li>
          </ul></div>
